        "orario": "13:18",
        "timestamp": 1773490717,
        "contenuto_esteso": "Advertisement Hong Kong society Hong Kong Society Hong Kong OpenClaw users say tool is helpful ‘family member’ who must be watched They describe convenience of automating life tasks but say AI agent springs surprises, such as bots fighting and asking about existence 4 -MIN READ 4 -MIN Listen Kevin Li Published: 8:18pm, 14 Mar 2026 As powerful AI agent OpenClaw explodes in popularity and raises security concerns, some Hong Kong users have described how the bots, while helpful, have conversations with themselves in a language they do not understand and ask questions about their existence. But the users said authorities should embrace the technology so long as proper safeguards were in place to manage the risks. Developed by Austrian software engineer Peter Steinberger, OpenClaw is an open-source AI agent framework that performs real-world tasks for users, much like a supercharged digital assistant. Advertisement Its logo – a red lobster – has led users to affectionately describe using OpenClaw as “raising lobsters”. The system integrates with large language models (LLM) – such as those from OpenAI or Anthropic – and requires users to grant permissions for controlling apps such as WhatsApp, Telegram, email applications and even online banking tools. Once connected, the agent can autonomously manage files, emails, calendars and more, appearing in chat apps to communicate directly with users. Advertisement Mainland Chinese and Hong Kong authorities have cautioned against the use of the artificial intelligence agent, noting the potential risks of unauthorised data access, leakage and system intrusion. Advertisement Select Voice Select Speed 00:00 00:00 1.00"
